    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-08-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-08-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="31"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d31">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The President’s Special Assistant</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to Prime Minister <persName type="to"
                            >Churchill</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-28">August 28,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>51. Personal and secret to the Prime Minister from Harry L. Hopkins.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Winston</hi>: I am feeling ever so much better but am
                    still taking things pretty easy and I am inclined to think that I will not risk
                    the dangers of a setback by fighting the Battle of Quebec. Better men than I
                    have been killed there.<note n="1" xml:id="d31fn1">For Churchill’s
                        interpretation of Hopkins’ absence from the Second Quebec Conference, see
                        Churchill, <hi rend="italic">Triumph and Tragedy</hi>, pp. 149, 161. Cf.
                        Sherwood, p. 814.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harry</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d31fn2">The source text also has the holograph signature
                        “Harry L Hopkins”, but only the given name “Harry” was to be transmitted at
                        the end of the message.</note>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
